      <title>Re: Test Server Update 11/8/2004</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=testupdate&amp;message.id=431#M431</link>
      <description>Harmful, I can see where you are coming from there but that's something that will need to be considered by the designers.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Bheran &amp; Healerith, the population of the playerbase is always something we pay close attention to. Server populations and guild memberships are things that will always have a certain amount of turnover even in the best conditions. My own experience as a player has shown me that when guilds that are stable for a long time suffer from loss of key people that often times the remnants of the guild is too slow to recruit new people. This has the compounding effect of making it harder for the rest of the guild to stick together since they can no longer do what they used to be able to do and morale drops. My suggestion to you is if maintaining guild strength is important to you, then you need to be as open with guild recruitment as you can stand to be. Regardless, just try to have fun because ultimately that's what it's all about. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Healerith, your question about Nature's Blight is not something I have the answer to and the person I think could answer it best is on vacation right now. Probably a good idea to try to get this subject going on your class forum somewhere since it's really a tuning issue you are bringing up.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Meresya/Polara, we did make a change where a bard getting feign death effects will cause the last song to stop. That was definitely a bug and should be fixed at this point. It was missed in the release notes. As for the fizzle rate issue, I can't speak for the design staff schedule about reviewing the situation. I do know that preliminary tests show that the fizzle rates are consistent with the fizzle rates associated with the spells that were tested, but this was only a preliminary test on a few songs that were allowed to be cast about 30,000 times each. At this point, the designers have the means to verify the fizzle rates are matching what they specify for the songs (as in, we are able to determine empirically that there are no code bugs causing more fizzles than expected), and the issue of if they fizzle too much is something that needs to be discussed with the designers at this point. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;MartosMT, the tuning issues you bring up are clearly important to you but unfortunately this thread probably isn't the best way to affect changes since it's just a test server code update thread and I don't have much say in that stuff.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Seffrid, sorry you've had an unpleasant experience. There's a lot of people that work at keeping EQ going - 50+ on the dev team alone, and a good number of QA, hardware IT guys, and probably more people than I realize - and it's not always possible to get every bug to the right people. I'm the right person to fix this sky issue you describe, and I'll ask QA to try to identify what is going on. Everything has been working to the best of my knowledge, perhaps it's a specific hardware configuration bug. It wouldn't be the first time.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Felrynn_FD, I looked at your JPGs and what is going on there is due to some settings that just need to be tweaked. The new sky system does render things differently and the 'horizon band' as we call it is something that should not be so visible. I'll ask about getting some time spent on making this look better.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Vjik, I don't have any information about Turn Undead AA, sorry I can't be more helpful there. The main person to ask is on vacation right now.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Hope that answers some questions,</description>
