      <description>&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Grumbuk-Dev wrote:&lt;br&gt;I can see from the pictures what people are referring to. The reason why this hasn't hit my list as a bug is because it is in fact working properly, it just isn't using settings that are what you (and the people you are referring to) would like. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The fact is, fog is going to be different now and the sky will probably never go back to the DX8 look. The artists always try to tune the settings as best they can to make it look as good as possible, which if they want can be pretty close to the old system but it will never be exactly the same as the DX8 sky/fog. Based on the feedback I'll suggest the settings get reviewed, perhaps they can be improved to the satisfaction of more players.&lt;br&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;I'm glad that least now you guys can see what us players are refering to as the "fog issue".  Any steps you take to try to reduce this problem is much appreciated.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;While I understand that its impossible to get the DX8 look back 100%, it should be possible to replicate the look nearly exactly by simply preventing the distance fog from being drawn against the skybox, and only have it drawn against terrain/objects.  If you look at the old screenshots I posted, you can clearly see that while the terrain is fading out in the distance, the sky is clearly drawn all the way down to the point where it meets the horizon.  Thats the way the old engine did it (going back to the DX6 engine), so it should be a simple programming change to redo how the fog is drawn.  Preventing the fog from being drawn against the sky should effictivly remove the "band" of fog all of us are complaining about.  The other issue is the *color* of the fog.  The old fog was a greyish color, not a blinding white.  Hopefully these changes can be instituted so we can enjoy our favorite pastime again.</description>
